33, provides important interpretations of this tumultuous and conflict-ridden period and invites readers to partake in the ongoing debate over modern Jewish identities and cultures. Marked at the outset by emancipation and the emergence of modern anti-Semitism, the period witnessed a profound transformation of Jewish social, political, and religious life culminating in the renaissance of Jewish cultures on the eve of the Holocaust. This textbook unites studies that inform our understanding of this historical epoch to this day as well as important historical revisions. Amongst the many contributions are texts by Michael Brenner, Willi Goetschel, Marion Kaplan, George L. Mosse, Peter Pulzer, and Till van Rahden.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aJewszGermanyxHistoryy1800-1933. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh1 aAschheim, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarkai, Avraham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBechtel, Delphine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrenner, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrenner, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoetschel, Willi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMosse, George L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPulzer, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRahden, Till van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoemer, Nils, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoemer, Nils, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 a